# EUIL - Extensible UI Language

EUIL (pronounced "you-ohl") is a simple UI library for creating Tkinter applications with XML.
You can make entire apps with this language.

## Features

- Support for most Tkinter and ttk widgets
- Custom widget attributes and styling
- Event handling and callbacks
- Automatic layouts like grids.

## Limitations

- <span style="color: red;"><strong>NOT PRODUCTION READY</strong></span>
- Limited support for advanced features
- Many bugs, hasn't been tested much with complex apps.

## Installation

1. Clone this repository
2. Ensure you have Python installed (3.12+ recommended, older versions not tested)

## Basic Usage

1. Create an EUIL file (e.g., `app.euil`) with your app structure
2. Create a Python file to load and run your app.

### Example app

app.euil:
```xml
<Window title="My App" width="800" height="600">
    <Frame padding="5">
        <Label text="Hello, World!" />
        <Button text="Click me" action="on_button_click" />
    </Frame>
</Window>
```

app.py:
```python
import EUIL # Import the EUIL library

def on_button_click(): # The function to be called when the button is clicked
    print("Button clicked!")

handlers = { # Bindings for functions, used in the action attribute of widgets such as buttons
    'on_button_click': on_button_click
}

with open("app.euil", "r") as f: # Read the app's contents for use in EUIL.build_ui()
    app = f.read()

root = EUIL.build_ui(app, handlers) # Build and run the app.
root.mainloop()
```

## XML Structure

### Root Element
```xml
<Window title="My App" width="800" height="600">
    <!-- Widgets go here -->
</Window>
```

### Basic Widgets

#### Frame
```xml
<Frame padding="5">
    <!-- Child widgets -->
</Frame>
```

#### Button
```xml
<Button text="Click me" action="on_button_click" />
```

#### Label
```xml
<Label text="Hello, World!" />
```

#### Entry
```xml
<Entry id="username" width="30" />
```

#### Checkbutton
```xml
<Check text="Enable feature" id="feature_toggle" />
```

### Layout

#### Grid Layout
```xml
<Grid columns="2" rowspacing="5" columnspacing="5">
    <Label text="Username:" />
    <Entry id="username" />
    <Label text="Password:" />
    <Entry id="password" show="â€¢" />
</Grid>
```

#### Notebook (Tabs)
```xml
<Notebook>
    <Frame text="Tab 1">
        <!-- Tab 1 content -->
    </Frame>
    <Frame text="Tab 2">
        <!-- Tab 2 content -->
    </Frame>
</Notebook>
```

#### Menu
```xml
<Menu>
    <Menu text="File">
        <Command label="New" command="new_file" />
        <Command label="Open" command="open_file" />
        <Separator />
        <Command label="Exit" command="exit_app" />
    </Menu>
    <Menu text="Help">
        <Command label="About" command="show_about" />
    </Menu>
</Menu>
```

## Widget Reference

### Common Attributes
- `id`: Unique identifier for the widget
- `text`: Display text (for labels, buttons, etc.)
- `width`, `height`: Dimensions in characters/pixels
- `padding`: Internal padding
- `style`: Custom style name
- `command`: Function to be called when the widget is interacted with
- `action`: Same as command.

### Supported Widgets

| Widget Tag | Description |
|------------|-------------|
| `Frame` | Container for other widgets |
| `Button` | Clickable button |
| `Label` | Text display |
| `Entry` | Single-line text input |
| `Text` | Multi-line text input |
| `Check` | Checkbox |
| `Radio` | Radio button |
| `Combo` | Dropdown list |
| `List` | Listbox |
| `Menu` | Menu bar |
| `Notebook` | Tabbed interface |
| `Panedwin` | Resizable panes |
| `Progress` | Progress bar |
| `Scale` | Slider control |
| `Scroll` | Scrollbar |
| `Separator` | Visual separator |

## Event Handling

1. Define your handler functions in Python:
   ```python
   def on_button_click():
       print("Button clicked!")
   ```

2. Map the handler names in your handlers dictionary:
   ```python
   handlers = {
       'on_button_click': on_button_click
   }
   ```

3. Reference the handler in your XML:
   ```xml
   <Button text="Click me" action="on_button_click" />
   ```

## Styling

EUIL supports basic styling through widget attributes.
For advanced theming, you can access the underlying ttk.Style object:

```python
style = ttk.Style()
style.configure('TButton', font=('Arial', 12))
style.configure('TLabel', foreground='blue')
```

## Examples

See the `example.euil` and `example.py` files (in the example folder)
for a complete example application.

